  "success": true,
  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python CLI/scraper (no frontend ‚Äî `find`/`git ls-files` confirm no `package.json`, no `.jsx`/`.tsx`, so the \"React re-renders\" ask doesn't apply here). I checked `store.py`, `pipeline.py`, `filters.py`, `fetchers.py`, `agent.py`, `notify.py`, and the GH Actions schedule instead. Real issues below, all reproducible from the code as written.\n\n### 1. N+1 query ‚Äî `Store.diff()` (store.py:55‚Äì74) ‚Äî **highest impact**\n\nEvery job triggers its own `SELECT`, in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nThis runs every 12h (`.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`) across ~114 configured sources (`sources.yaml`), several of which paginate up to 40 pages √ó 10 jobs (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google) ‚Äî easily thousands of individual round trips per run.\n\n**Fix**: one batched `SELECT ... WHERE key IN (...)` to build a lookup dict, then `executemany` for writes. Chunk to stay under SQLite's host-parameter limit:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    if not jobs:\n        return [], []\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(jobs), 500):          # stay under SQLITE_MAX_VARIABLE_NUMBER\n        chunk = jobs[i:i + 500]\n        keys = [j.key for j in chunk]\n        ph = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(keys))\n        existing.update(\n            (r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"])\n            for r in self.conn.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({ph})\", keys)\n        )\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    inserts, updates = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}      # compute key/content_hash once (see #3)\n        h = row[\"content_hash\"]\n        if job.key not in existing:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif existing[job.key] != h:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n            location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range, content_hash,\n            first_seen, last_seen) VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,\n            :location,:department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\"\"\",\n            updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns `O(N)` round trips into `O(N/500)`.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation ‚Äî `filters.py:11‚Äì41`\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside itself** ‚Äî recompiling the same keyword patterns from scratch for every single job:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nWith thousands of jobs and a handful of keywords, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls per run.\n\n**Fix**: compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass compiled patterns through:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation ‚Äî `Job.content_hash` / `Job.key` (models.py:55‚Äì69)\n\nBoth are plain `@property`, so every access recomputes. `content_hash` does a SHA-256 hash of a joined string; in `Store.diff()` it's currently computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `to_row()` for the write ‚Äî 2x per changed job, needlessly. The batched `diff()` above already fixes this by computing `job.to_row()` once per job and reusing the dict. If you want it cached independent of that, since `Job` uses `slots=True` you can't use `functools.cached_property` for free ‚Äî add an explicit cache slot, or (simplest) just compute `to_row()` once at each call site as shown above.\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity ‚Äî no HTTP conditional requests across scheduled runs\n\nThe pipeline re-fetches every board fresh every 12h forever (`fetch_all` in fetchers.py), even for ATS boards that haven't changed. Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby/etc. all send `ETag`/`Last-Modified` on their JSON endpoints. Store the last `ETag` per source in the existing `meta` table and send `If-None-Match`; a `304` skips parsing entirely:\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json(client, url, *, etag_key=None, store=None, **kw):\n    headers = kw.pop(\"headers\", {})\n    if etag_key and store and (etag := store.get_meta(etag_key)):\n        headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag\n    r = await _request(client, url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return None\n    if etag_key and store and (tag := r.headers.get(\"ETag\")):\n        store.set_meta(etag_key, tag)\n    return r.json()\n```\nThis is the biggest wall-clock win for the scheduled job since it saves both the network round trip and the parse for boards that haven't posted anything new ‚Äî likely the majority of the ~114 sources on any given 12h run.\n\n### 5. Missing index ‚Äî `Store.added_since()` (store.py:111‚Äì119)\n\n```python\nreturn self.conn.execute(\n    \"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\", (ts,)).fetchall()\n```\nThe schema only indexes `company` (store.py:27); `first_seen` (used in both the `WHERE` and `ORDER BY`) does a full table scan + sort. Used by `agent.py db-new`, run on every scan. Add:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n### 6. Unbounded growth (\"leak\" analog) ‚Äî stale rows never pruned\n\n`jobs.db` only ever grows: postings that get pulled down stay in the `jobs` table forever with a stale `last_seen`, and the file is committed back to git every 12h (`scrape.yaml`), permanently. Over months this bloats both the DB (slowing every `diff()`/`added_since()` call) and the git history/clone size. Consider a periodic purge:\n\n```python\ndef prune_stale(self, older_than_days: int = 90) -> int:\n    cutoff = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=older_than_days)).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.execute(\"DELETE FROM jobs WHERE last_seen < ?\", (cutoff,))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return cur.rowcount\n```\n\n### Not applicable\n- **N+1 elsewhere**: fetchers.py's pagination loops (Twosigma/Optiver/Microsoft/Netflix/Amazon/Google) are already correctly batched HTTP calls with a shared `httpx.AsyncClient` and bounded `Semaphore(8)` ‚Äî no fix needed there.\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend code exists in this repo.\n- **Memory leaks**: the client/DB lifecycle is handled correctly (`async with`/`with` everywhere, `finally: await client.aclose()` in `fetch_all`); nothing long-running enough to leak in the traditional sense.\n\nHighest ROI order: **#1 (N+1 diff)** and **#4 (conditional HTTP caching)** first ‚Äî both scale with total job count and run every 12h forever ‚Äî then #2, #5, #6.\n",
